1
00:00:00,483 --> 00:00:01,996
No. I'm still looking.

2
00:00:02,723 --> 00:00:05,112
You know, Lois, I wanted to ask you
about that artic...

3
00:00:05,283 --> 00:00:08,639
Hey, I'm gonna run downstairs
for some fresh air. Great!

4
00:00:21,843 --> 00:00:23,481
Thanks.

5
00:00:30,963 --> 00:00:33,602
- Let's talk when I get back.
- Sure.

6
00:01:24,923 --> 00:01:27,562
You know, you really
shouldn't smoke, Miss Lane.

7
00:01:30,723 --> 00:01:33,112
- Sorry. Didn't mean to startle you.
- I'm fine. Really.

8
00:01:35,163 --> 00:01:38,155
I just wasn't expecting you.

9
00:01:38,803 --> 00:01:40,316
With all the press on the plane...

10
00:01:40,483 --> 00:01:42,792
...I wasn't sure it was
the best time for us to talk.

11
00:01:42,963 --> 00:01:46,000
Well, there's no press around now.
Except for me, of course.

12
00:01:48,123 --> 00:01:50,478
I know people are asking questions
now that I'm back.

13
00:01:50,843 --> 00:01:54,233
I think it's only fair
that I answer those people.

14
00:01:55,843 --> 00:01:59,040
So you're here for an interview?

15
00:02:00,243 --> 00:02:01,232
Okay, then.

16
00:02:04,963 --> 00:02:06,874
- Where did I put that thing?
- Right pocket.

17
00:02:12,763 --> 00:02:15,357
Let's start with the big question.

18
00:02:15,523 --> 00:02:17,912
- Where'd you go?
- To Krypton.

19
00:02:18,083 --> 00:02:20,358
But you told me it was destroyed.
Ages ago.

20
00:02:20,523 --> 00:02:21,922
It was.

21
00:02:22,083 --> 00:02:24,358
But when astronomers
thought they found it...

22
00:02:25,763 --> 00:02:28,038
...I had to see for myself.

23
00:02:31,523 --> 00:02:35,198
Well, you're back, and everyone
seems to be pretty happy about it.

24
00:02:38,283 --> 00:02:39,682
Not everyone.

25
00:02:40,803 --> 00:02:43,112
- I read the article, Lois.
- So did a lot of people.

26
00:02:43,283 --> 00:02:46,116
- Tomorrow they're giving me the Pulitzer...
- Why did you write it?

27
00:02:47,723 --> 00:02:49,679
How could you leave us like that?

28
00:02:51,123 --> 00:02:53,432
I moved on. So did the rest of us.

29
00:02:53,923 --> 00:02:55,356
That's why I wrote it.

30
00:02:55,523 --> 00:02:58,196
The world doesn't need a savior.

31
00:02:58,603 --> 00:03:00,434
And neither do I.

32
00:03:14,963 --> 00:03:15,998
Lois.

33
00:03:17,643 --> 00:03:19,998
Will you come with me?

34
00:03:21,683 --> 00:03:23,196
Why?

35
00:03:23,563 --> 00:03:25,599
There's something I wanna show you.

36
00:03:31,603 --> 00:03:33,321
Please.

37
00:03:43,883 --> 00:03:45,953
I can't be gone long.

38
00:03:46,123 --> 00:03:47,954
You won't be.

39
00:03:59,843 --> 00:04:02,482
Clark said the reason you left
without saying goodbye...

40
00:04:02,643 --> 00:04:04,838
...is because it was
too unbearable for you.

41
00:04:05,003 --> 00:04:07,517
Personally, I think that's a load of crap.

42
00:04:08,083 --> 00:04:11,120
- Clark?
- He's just a guy I work with.

43
00:04:12,163 --> 00:04:14,199
Maybe Clark's right.

44
00:04:17,443 --> 00:04:19,479
You know, my...

45
00:04:19,643 --> 00:04:24,478
Richard, he's a pilot.
He takes me up all the time.

46
00:04:25,603 --> 00:04:27,514
Not like this.

47
00:04:41,763 --> 00:04:44,072
I forgot how warm you were.

48
00:05:13,443 --> 00:05:14,876
Listen.

49
00:05:15,723 --> 00:05:17,554
What do you hear?

50
00:05:18,243 --> 00:05:19,437
Nothing.

51
00:05:23,203 --> 00:05:24,875
I hear everything.

52
00:05:28,203 --> 00:05:30,717
You wrote that the world
doesn't need a savior...

53
00:05:32,003 --> 00:05:35,200
...but every day
I hear people crying for one.

54
00:05:47,523 --> 00:05:50,083
I'm sorry I left you, Lois.

55
00:05:53,803 --> 00:05:55,759
I'll take you back now.

56
00:08:03,443 --> 00:08:05,001
Richard's a good man.

57
00:08:08,283 --> 00:08:10,399
And you've been gone a long time.

58
00:08:12,963 --> 00:08:14,476
I know.

59
00:08:19,043 --> 00:08:20,317
I...

60
00:08:25,323 --> 00:08:27,234
So will I see you around?

61
00:08:28,203 --> 00:08:30,114
I'm always around.

62
00:08:31,363 --> 00:08:33,001
Good night, Lois.

63
00:08:51,203 --> 00:08:54,912
We're having beef, honey. Do you want
the tofu wrap or the veggie wrap?

64
00:08:58,680 --> 00:09:00,193
You all right?

65
00:09:02,127 --> 00:09:03,313
Where have you been?

66
00:09:07,912 --> 00:09:12,161
I was up on the roof, getting some air.

67
00:09:13,154 --> 00:09:15,031
Tell the truth now.

68
00:09:21,314 --> 00:09:22,429
Were you smoking?

69
00:09:24,954 --> 00:09:26,626
No.

70
00:09:35,074 --> 00:09:36,223
Is this real?

71
00:09:37,234 --> 00:09:39,031
- Where'd you find him?
- He found me.

72
00:09:39,194 --> 00:09:41,867
Oh, this is great. I can't wait to read it.

73
00:09:42,034 --> 00:09:44,343
So, Mr. White, about the blackout...

74
00:09:44,514 --> 00:09:46,903
Lois, this is the biggest night
of your life.

75
00:09:47,074 --> 00:09:49,144
Have you picked out a dress?
Something snazzy?

76
00:09:50,114 --> 00:09:52,708
It just feels a little weird
winning for that article.

77
00:09:52,874 --> 00:09:55,786
- It just doesn't seem right.
- What doesn't seem right?

78
00:09:55,954 --> 00:09:59,390
Winning an award for an article called
"Why the World Doesn't Need Superman."

79
00:09:59,554 --> 00:10:01,909
When, according
to this newspaper, they do.

80
00:10:02,074 --> 00:10:04,872
Lois, Pulitzer Prizes
are like Academy Awards.

81
00:10:05,034 --> 00:10:08,026
Nobody remembers what you got one for.
It's just that you got one.

82
00:10:08,194 --> 00:10:11,186
- But...
- This is your night. You enjoy it.

83
00:10:11,354 --> 00:10:13,788
I'm sure Kent's on the blackout.

84
00:11:11,874 --> 00:11:13,990
Department of Water and Power, please.

85
00:11:14,674 --> 00:11:15,902
7782, great.

86
00:11:17,314 --> 00:11:18,747
Metropolis Public Works.

87
00:11:18,914 --> 00:11:21,303
Hi, Stephen, Lois Lane
from the <i>Daily Planet.</i> Blackout?

88
00:11:21,474 --> 00:11:24,068
I just need a little info
on a few outstanding power grids.

89
00:11:24,234 --> 00:11:25,792
<i>Yeah, I do have it here, actually.</i>

90
00:11:25,954 --> 00:11:29,788
<i>So the uptown grid went dark at 12:36</i>
<i>and midtown 10 seconds before.</i>

91
00:11:29,954 --> 00:11:31,387
Which grid was hit first?

92
00:11:31,554 --> 00:11:32,828
<i>It just reads Vanderworth.</i>

93
00:11:32,994 --> 00:11:35,269
- Across the river?
- <i>6 Springwood Drive.</i>

94
00:11:35,434 --> 00:11:37,584
6 Springwood Drive.
A residence or a business?

95
00:11:37,754 --> 00:11:39,426
- <i>Residence.</i>
- Sure? Nothing before that?

96
00:11:39,594 --> 00:11:41,824
- <i>That's all it shows.</i>
- Thank you very much.

97
00:11:43,594 --> 00:11:44,822
Oh, Jason.

98
00:11:51,354 --> 00:11:54,426
- There's your mom, Jason.
- You're late, Mommy.

99
00:12:02,314 --> 00:12:05,033
Where are we? Is this the Pulitzer?

100
00:12:05,194 --> 00:12:09,312
Nope. I've just gotta ask these people
a few questions and then we can go.

101
00:12:23,034 --> 00:12:25,309
Can I stay in the car?

102
00:12:25,834 --> 00:12:27,347
No, honey.

103
00:12:33,754 --> 00:12:37,952
- Are we trespassing?
- No. Yes.

104
00:12:52,074 --> 00:12:53,826
Hello?

105
00:13:24,034 --> 00:13:25,513
Hello?

106
00:13:36,154 --> 00:13:38,622
I like the curly one.

107
00:13:45,634 --> 00:13:48,353
Let's go. This was a bad idea.

108
00:14:03,434 --> 00:14:05,152
Lex Luthor.

109
00:14:07,074 --> 00:14:09,110
Lois Lane?

110
00:14:14,674 --> 00:14:15,948
You're bald.

111
00:14:35,234 --> 00:14:36,553
And what is your name?

112
00:14:36,714 --> 00:14:39,069
I'm not supposed to talk to strangers.

113
00:14:39,554 --> 00:14:41,431
- Cute kid, and smart.
- Thanks.

114
00:14:41,594 --> 00:14:44,666
We're not really strangers, are we?
This is kind of a little reunion.

115
00:14:44,834 --> 00:14:46,790
Heck, I'm a fan.

116
00:14:46,954 --> 00:14:48,387
I love your writing...

117
00:14:49,194 --> 00:14:50,946
...and your dress.
- I love your boat.

118
00:14:51,114 --> 00:14:53,628
How'd you get it?
Swindle some widow out of her money?

119
00:14:54,914 --> 00:14:57,064
That's funny. Didn't you win
the Pulitzer Prize...

120
00:14:57,234 --> 00:15:00,670
...for my favorite article of all time, "Why
the World Doesn't Need Superman"?

121
00:15:00,834 --> 00:15:04,588
Didn't you have a few more years to go
on that double life sentence?

122
00:15:04,754 --> 00:15:06,904
Yes, well, we can thank
the Man of Steel for that.

123
00:15:07,074 --> 00:15:10,225
I mean, he's really good at swooping in
and catching the bad guys...

124
00:15:10,394 --> 00:15:13,784
...but he's not so hot at the little things,
like Miranda rights...

125
00:15:13,954 --> 00:15:18,470
...due process, making your court date.

126
00:15:18,634 --> 00:15:20,989
Did you have anything to do
with the blackout?

127
00:15:23,874 --> 00:15:25,990
Are you fishing for an interview,
Miss Lane?

128
00:15:26,154 --> 00:15:28,224
It's been a while
since you've been a headline.

129
00:15:28,394 --> 00:15:30,464
Maybe it's time
people knew your name again.

130
00:15:31,114 --> 00:15:34,902
How about we turn this boat around,
call a cab for my son...

131
00:15:35,434 --> 00:15:37,948
...and then you can do
whatever you want with me.

132
00:15:38,634 --> 00:15:41,068
No, I don't think we'll be
turning around, Miss Lane...

133
00:15:41,234 --> 00:15:43,748
...which means that
we do have some time to kill.

134
00:15:45,834 --> 00:15:47,631
How about that interview?

135
00:15:48,514 --> 00:15:51,711
Yeah, just call me if you hear anything.
Okay. Thank you.

136
00:15:51,874 --> 00:15:53,512
So, what did the school say?

137
00:15:53,674 --> 00:15:55,107
She picked him up at 3:15.

138
00:15:59,194 --> 00:16:02,345
- Hi, I heard about Lois.
- Yes, come in, Clark, come in.

139
00:16:02,514 --> 00:16:04,903
- Is there anything I can do?
- Yeah, you're a reporter.

140
00:16:05,074 --> 00:16:07,713
- Help Richard track her down.
- I'll check her computer.

141
00:16:07,874 --> 00:16:09,068
Excuse me, Clark.

142
00:16:22,234 --> 00:16:25,192
What do you know about crystals?

143
00:16:25,354 --> 00:16:26,992
They make great chandeliers.

144
00:16:27,554 --> 00:16:32,344
This crystal may seem unremarkable,
but so is the seed of a redwood tree.

145
00:16:32,514 --> 00:16:35,790
It's how our mutual friend in tights
made his Arctic getaway spot.

146
00:16:35,954 --> 00:16:37,751
Cute. It's a little small for my taste.

147
00:16:37,914 --> 00:16:39,393
You're building an island?

148
00:16:40,554 --> 00:16:43,751
You're not seeing
the big picture here, Miss Lane.

149
00:16:43,914 --> 00:16:46,109
Let me enlarge it for you.

150
00:16:48,594 --> 00:16:51,870
Not just an island,
an entirely new continent.

151
00:16:52,034 --> 00:16:55,151
An extinct world, reborn on our own.

152
00:16:55,314 --> 00:16:56,667
Why?

153
00:16:59,554 --> 00:17:01,385
Land, Miss Lane.

154
00:17:01,554 --> 00:17:04,193
I mean... Kitty, what did my father
used to say to me?

155
00:17:04,354 --> 00:17:05,707
"You're losing your hair"?

156
00:17:06,674 --> 00:17:08,505
- Before that.
- "Get out"?

157
00:17:09,994 --> 00:17:12,189
He said, "You can print money...

158
00:17:12,354 --> 00:17:14,868
...manufacture diamonds,
and people are a dime a dozen...

159
00:17:15,034 --> 00:17:17,992
...but they'll always need land."

160
00:17:18,154 --> 00:17:20,873
It's the one thing
they're not making any more of.

161
00:17:21,394 --> 00:17:23,669
But the United States...

162
00:17:25,314 --> 00:17:28,670
Will be underwater.

163
00:17:29,074 --> 00:17:30,587
It's simple physics, Miss Lane.

164
00:17:30,754 --> 00:17:33,427
Two objects cannot occupy
the same space at the same time.

165
00:17:33,594 --> 00:17:36,028
And the rest of the world
will just let you keep it?

166
00:17:36,194 --> 00:17:38,310
- They'll...
- They'll...

167
00:17:38,794 --> 00:17:40,193
...what?

168
00:17:40,354 --> 00:17:43,107
I'll have advanced alien technology...

169
00:17:43,274 --> 00:17:46,186
...thousands of years beyond
what anyone could throw at me.

170
00:17:46,354 --> 00:17:48,310
Bring it on!

171
00:17:49,274 --> 00:17:51,105
And eventually...

172
00:17:51,274 --> 00:17:53,504
...the rest of the world
will be begging me...

173
00:17:53,674 --> 00:17:56,188
...for a piece of high-tech
beachfront property.

174
00:17:56,354 --> 00:17:58,584
In fact, they'll pay
through the nose for it.

175
00:17:58,994 --> 00:18:00,666
But millions of people will die.

176
00:18:00,834 --> 00:18:03,348
Billions! Once again,
the press underestimates me.

177
00:18:03,514 --> 00:18:05,789
This is front-page news.

178
00:18:06,434 --> 00:18:08,345
Come on, let me hear you say it
just once.

179
00:18:08,514 --> 00:18:12,826
- You're insane.
- No! Not that. No, the other thing.

180
00:18:12,994 --> 00:18:16,509
It's dangling off the tip of your tongue.
Let me hear it just once, please?

181
00:18:16,674 --> 00:18:19,552
- Superman will never...
- Wrong!

182
00:18:32,234 --> 00:18:33,792
What is that?

183
00:18:34,954 --> 00:18:37,627
I think you know exactly what this is.

184
00:18:43,394 --> 00:18:46,147
Mind over muscle, Miss Lane.

185
00:18:47,234 --> 00:18:48,952
Mind...

186
00:18:56,194 --> 00:18:58,105
Who is that boy's father?

187
00:18:59,554 --> 00:19:01,351
Richard.

188
00:19:01,794 --> 00:19:05,150
<i>Mr. Luthor, we're approaching</i>
<i>the coordinates.</i>

189
00:19:05,714 --> 00:19:07,227
Are you sure?

190
00:19:07,394 --> 00:19:12,514
<i>Yes, sir. Latitude 40 degrees north,</i>
<i>longitude 73 degrees west.</i>

191
00:19:33,154 --> 00:19:35,224
Don't let them leave this room.

192
00:19:35,554 --> 00:19:38,022
Kitty, come with me.
You're not gonna want to miss this.

193
00:20:48,114 --> 00:20:49,433
- Damn it.
- What?

194
00:20:49,594 --> 00:20:50,743
She has a password.

195
00:20:52,674 --> 00:20:54,187
"Jason."

196
00:20:56,194 --> 00:20:57,832
"Richard."

197
00:20:59,674 --> 00:21:01,187
Try "Superman."

198
00:21:06,114 --> 00:21:08,423
"Superman." Great.

199
00:21:16,434 --> 00:21:18,425
Don't touch that, honey.

200
00:21:22,514 --> 00:21:24,869
Why don't you go play the piano.

201
00:23:17,314 --> 00:23:19,703
Come on, come on, come on.

202
00:25:02,394 --> 00:25:05,306
Lex, this isn't like the train set.

203
00:25:07,154 --> 00:25:08,826
I know.

204
00:25:14,634 --> 00:25:16,352
Come on, come on.

205
00:25:16,954 --> 00:25:18,103
Come on.

206
00:26:42,434 --> 00:26:44,231
- Honey, are you okay?
- Yeah.

207
00:26:44,394 --> 00:26:46,305
- Are you hurt?
- I'm fine.

208
00:26:47,474 --> 00:26:50,113
Open this door! Open it!

209
00:27:04,834 --> 00:27:07,109
Could you help Mommy open the door?

210
00:27:09,874 --> 00:27:11,546
I'm sorry.

211
00:27:14,514 --> 00:27:16,505
It's gonna be okay.

212
00:27:16,674 --> 00:27:18,904
Okay? It's gonna be okay.

213
00:27:37,794 --> 00:27:41,104
We had a little problem downstairs.

214
00:27:41,634 --> 00:27:43,704
Brutus is dead.

215
00:27:44,354 --> 00:27:47,471
He got hit with the piano.

216
00:27:51,874 --> 00:27:53,671
Where's the boy?

217
00:27:53,834 --> 00:27:57,793
With the mother,
locked up in the pantry.

218
00:27:59,874 --> 00:28:01,944
Oh, it's time for us to go.

219
00:28:07,714 --> 00:28:10,103
My camera's not working.

220
00:28:10,874 --> 00:28:12,910
And my phone's not working.

221
00:28:17,754 --> 00:28:20,393
- Okay, I'm good.
- That was weird.

222
00:28:34,754 --> 00:28:36,984
Hey, guys.
This just came through the fax.

223
00:28:37,154 --> 00:28:39,349
It's Lois' handwriting,
I'd recognize it anywhere.

224
00:28:39,514 --> 00:28:41,266
I just... No idea
what the numbers mean.

225
00:28:41,434 --> 00:28:43,106
- They're coordinates.
- Coordinates.

226
00:28:45,154 --> 00:28:46,303
That's just off the coast.

227
00:28:46,474 --> 00:28:49,466
Jimmy, tell Perry I'm taking the seaplane.
Keep trying her cell.

228
00:30:48,554 --> 00:30:49,953
What are these, lottery numbers?

229
00:30:50,474 --> 00:30:52,385
I think they're coordinates, chief.

230
00:31:29,514 --> 00:31:30,629
Chief...

231
00:31:56,434 --> 00:31:58,629
Come on! Move it!

232
00:34:16,434 --> 00:34:18,106
Chief!

233
00:34:28,794 --> 00:34:31,103
Great Caesar's ghost.

234
00:36:32,874 --> 00:36:34,910
- Daddy.
- Oh, my God.

235
00:36:47,954 --> 00:36:49,307
How did you get here?

236
00:36:49,474 --> 00:36:51,066
I flew.

237
00:36:54,594 --> 00:36:56,346
Look out!

238
00:37:08,674 --> 00:37:10,312
Mom!

239
00:37:10,474 --> 00:37:12,510
Mom! Mom!

240
00:37:12,674 --> 00:37:13,993
Jason, come here! Jason!

241
00:37:16,754 --> 00:37:18,585
Come here! Watch your head!
Come here!

242
00:38:16,634 --> 00:38:18,352
Mommy! Mom!

243
00:38:20,194 --> 00:38:21,388
Jason!

244
00:38:24,714 --> 00:38:26,147
Jason, hold on!

245
00:38:29,154 --> 00:38:31,714
- Have you got him?
- I got him! Go!

246
00:38:34,034 --> 00:38:35,547
Hold on! Hold on!

247
00:38:49,674 --> 00:38:50,948
- Mommy!
- Give him to me!

248
00:38:51,114 --> 00:38:52,627
Mommy!

249
00:38:53,234 --> 00:38:55,065
- Mommy! Mommy!
- Come on, Jason! Come on!

250
00:38:58,754 --> 00:39:01,473
- Lois! Lois!
- Mommy!

251
00:40:03,314 --> 00:40:05,305
Jason, get on my back.

252
00:40:34,114 --> 00:40:35,706
Give me your hand.

253
00:40:42,834 --> 00:40:45,029
- Have you got them?
- Yeah.

254
00:41:03,354 --> 00:41:05,185
Get buckled in!

255
